metadata.name: Pixel Management #913
metadata.description:
#tezpole has demonstrated to us all the importance of effective Cable Management. Intrigued by this challenge, I've delved deep into the pixels of this issue. 🙂

Drawing inspiration from Rev Dan Catt’s 'Tally!' and applying similar principles of Cable Management, I've assembled a fun and free OE project.

This project dynamically evolves with each iteration.Grid is determined by a random value calculated as follows: the lower bound starts at 3 and increases incrementally with every 100 iterations, while the upper bound starts at 4 and increases with every 30 iterations. In practical terms, as the iteration count increases, both the minimum and maximum possible number of cols&rows gradually increase.

3200x3200px
Press [s] for .jpeg | Press [p] for .png
Made with p5.js

Rob Scalera | 2023

metadata.name: sinuosity #94
metadata.description:
sinuosity is defined as:

- (n.) the ability to curve or bend easily and flexibly.

sinuous is defined as a couple of things:

- (adj.) having many curves and turns.
- (adj.) lithe and supple.

each curve anchors to the center. 

maybe that center is a life. (maybe that center is you.)

maybe that curve is a relationship. (or a job.) (or repressed trauma that needs processing.)

maybe that curve has other curves within. (it probably does.)

sometimes there are many curves at once. (usually this the case.) 

occasionally, there may only be one. (life isn’t always so complicated.) 

whatever curves the moment contains it can help to step away and see how they come together. (this is not always easy.)

[cc0] [p5js] [xoxo] [twitter: @heyjeres]

metadata.name: Wish You Were Here #13
metadata.description:
This artwork was created while experimenting with noise fields and it instantly evoked a feeling of nostalgia in me. It's coded entirely in p5.js and renders domain warped flow fields on a paper canvas-like texture.

Please note that it takes about 5-10 seconds for the artwork to start loading. And it’s best viewed on a screen bigger than a mobile phone, while listening to this track called ‘Wish You Were Here' by Pink Floyd: 
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hjpF8ukSrvk

Artwork loads at 1000px by 1000px resolution by default. Press ‘2’,’4’ or ‘8’ to load as 2000px by 2000px, 4000px by 4000px or 8000px by 8000px respectively.
Press 's' at any time to download the rendered resolution.

metadata.name: Washed Trees Fluor #60
metadata.description:
“Our Love had heard that an immortal language never could die, although silent, it still slept somewhere amongst the birches, lost ever since the day when we went weeping from beneath the angel-guarded gates of Eden.”

In Inner Purple Forest “Washed Trees Fluor”, rainbow bubbles-shaped form sprouts like fungi from a birch log. 

With its disconcerting conjunction of the natural and man-made, this still life recalls the way that nutrients in dead plant material are reclaimed by other living things as part of nature’s cycle of decay and rebirth.

No matter how long or hard we might gaze upon these ghostly images remain the same, they are not allowed to gather too much dust, they do not lose their bloom.

Seen it in the past, whenever a group comes together.
Graffiti scene / Demo scene / Art scene etc. etc. 
New rules start popping up,
you should do this, you should do that..
Can't do this do this, you should not do that.
New rules, that can hinder you. 
If you start conforming/obeying the rules

Like seen people, making lovely works,
'but it should have more variations'
Adding all kinds of extras, 
that only made the work 
less powerful in the end

Or loosing themselves 
in the small details

Making 100 great and lovely sketches,
and finally releasing a work 
that totally did not work or sell at all.

Such a shame.


Well, it does not have enough variations

Variations: != 100 different extras?

For example, look at the Mark's Smoll-skulls or like Casey Reas works,
or like 100 warhol soup-cans, all just a littlebit different

I knew a classic composer, 
that really enjoyed creating works
when he was young.
Became a teacher,
conform within the institution
And lost all the joy he had for composing,
due to pressure and rules 'how things should be done'


Don't post too much

Some people like to work on 1 painting for years
trying to create their own Mona Lisa.

While Vincent van Gogh would paint lightning fast,
sometimes doing 1 painting a day


Break the rules
Make your own rules
set yourself free.

metadata.name: what's left of what's left #29
metadata.description:
"The images is not a closed field of knowledge; it is a whirling, centrifugal field. It is not a fiedl of knowledge like any other; it is a movement demanding all the anthropogical aspects of being and time" Didi-Huberman

Continuing in the experimentation of photography and generative art.

What's left of what's left ... Seeks to take the reflection beyond the simple superimposition of images, highlighting the "human" x "machine" interaction.

The areas of light, fog and shadows present us with image clippings in a large tangle of visual reflections.

The algorithm builds unique images from the combination of different layers, according to a bank of photographs extracted from my own collection. In total, there are six layers containing 10 photographs each, in addition to a base layer containing 20 photos of urban fragments.

In addition, the code implements, in a random and semi-autonomous way, some adaptations such as masking, colorization, rotation and blending modes for specific layers.

* Features
Place - Where have i been. 20 distinct urban fragments;
Mode - “Color” 80% or “B&W” 20%;
Zone - “Amazon” 25%; “Mist” and “Terracotta” 20%, “Old Sky” 15%; and “Ocher” and “Golden” 10%.
Invert - 2.5%

"In a sense of overlapping past/future, not as an idea of ​​current time, but as places of memory dispute. This "non-place", traversed by layers, is solidified in the images, almost like a truce from the endless war of this inconstancy.
there is no winner" Raffa Gomes

Generative Token by of Morbeck for fxhash

august 21, 2022

metadata.name: Sedimentarias: Algorithmic Study #120
metadata.description:
“Sedimentarias” is the third algorithmic artwork of the quartet. This is an exploration to create an abstract artwork in continuation of my previous work, which consists of infinite harmonious possibilities for colors just like sedimentary rocks. Different color styles (multicolor, monochrome, black and white, etc.) and different forms and canvas sizes are included, And there are also some special modes in this work.

Open it in live view and press ’s’ to save the image with high resolution. It might take some time.

Made with p5js.
